.CENTER;^&<REFRESH <COMMAND <IN <ONCE\&
\\
.FILL.JUST
.PARA
^AFTER TYPING IN THE <'DATE' AND <'TIME', YOU MAY RECEIVE THE FOLLOWING
ERROR MESSAGE:
^^
.SKIP 1
.LM 11
.NOFILL.NOJUST
'RESERVED PAGE HAS ALREADY BEEN ALLOCATED'
\\
'^THE STRUCTURE <WAS <NOT SUCCESSFULLY REFRESHED.'
.LM 7
.FILL.JUST
.PARA
^THERE ARE TWO WAYS OF GETTING AROUND THIS.  ^THIS IS THE FIRST METHOD:
.LM 11
.SKIP 1
1) ^GET OUT OF <ONCE BY ENTERING CONTROL <X (_^<X) ON <CTTY.
.SKIP 1
2) <FTALOD THE <PAKCP5.SAV TAPE.
.SKIP 1
3)  ^DO A <LIST ON ALL DISK DRIVES AND <ZFORMAT ALL UNITS REPORTING
<BAD <REGIONS AND <BAD <SECTORS.
.SKIP 1
4) ^UPON COMPLETION, GET OUT OF <PACKCOPY AND <FTALOD THE SYSTEM
MONITOR TAPES.
.SKIP 1
5) ^BRING UP IN <CONSOLE MODE AND THEN CONTINUE WITH NORMAL <REBUILD
PROCEDURES.
.PARA
.LM 7
^THE SECOND METHOD IS:
.SKIP 1
.LM 11
1) ^AFTER RECEIVING THE ABOVE ERROR MESSAGE, ENTER '<TYP <BAT' AT
THE <FILES* PROMPT.
.SKIP 1
2) ^AFTER THE STATEMENT '^TYPE UNIT NAME' PRINTS OUT, ENTER THE
FIRST <BPA_#.
.SKIP 1
3) ^IF IT REPORTS '0 BAD PAGES IN 0', THEN IT IS OKAY.
.SKIP 1
4) ^IF IT REPORTS A NUMBER OF BAD PAGES THEN ENTER <'CHANGE <BAT'
WITH A <'YES' ANSWER AT THE NEXT <FILES* PROMPT.
.SKIP 1
5) ^REPEAT ^STEPS 1 THROUGH 4 ON ALL <BPA'S, <BPB'S, AND <BPC'S THAT YOU
ARE USING FOR THE <REBUILD.
.SKIP 1
6) ^AFTER ALL <UNITS HAVE BEEN CHECKED, ENTER <'REFRESH' AT THE
NEXT <FILES* PROMPT.
.SKIP 1
7) ^CONTINUE THE <REBUILD USING NORMAL PROCEDURES.
.PAGE
.CC
